			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://spanish-podcast.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/01/cocheholanda.jpg" alt="Coche Holanda" align="top" height="360" width="380" /></p>
<p>In the second part of this <strong>Voices en Español</strong> interview, Javier Barros del Villar talks about the different styles of street art he found in Europe, specifically Austria, Hungary and the Czech Republic.</p>
<p>There&#8217;s a word that Javier uses frequently in this podcast. It&#8217;s <em>cuate</em>. And it means buddy, friend or dude.</p>
<p>Also, the names of the street artists mentioned in this podcast are:</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://www.acamonchi-art.com/" target="_blank">Acamonchi</a></strong><br />
<strong><a href="http://www.tlachco.net/fs/" target="_blank"> Fuera de servicio </a></strong><a href="http://www.tlachco.net/fs/" target="_blank"></a><br />
<a href="http://www.watchavato.com.mx/index.html" target="_blank"><strong> Watchavato</strong> (Tijuana style)</a> <font size="-1"><span></span></font></p>
<p>Check out Javier&#8217;s blog (<strong><a href="http://arteycallejero.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">arte callejero</a></strong>) for more examples of street art in Mexico and from around the world.</p>
<p><img src="http://spanish-podcast.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/01/artecallefrancia.jpg" alt="ArteCalleFrancia" align="bottom" height="339" width="400" /></p>
<p><em>Examples of street art above in Holland (&#8220;<a href="http://arteycallejero.blogspot.com/search/label/Pa%C3%ADs%20Holanda">El agua es vida&#8221;</a>) and below in France (<a href="http://arteycallejero.blogspot.com/2008/01/so-alone.html">&#8220;So Alone&#8221;</a>)</em></p>
